<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Open Data Institute</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further Written Evidence from the Open Data Institute [OD 25]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">The government has released a National Action Plan and National Information Infrastructure but continues to find it hard to create a focused and coherent Open Data Strategy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">Attempting to restrict the beneficiaries of data (for example to prevent large multi-national companies from benefiting from it without paying) prevents </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">data</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt"> from flowing to those who need it.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">The publication of open data needs to be built in to every serv</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">ice that government procures</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">, both in IT systems and embedded in public sector services</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">Being a Trading Fund is not incompatible with opening data.</span></li></ul><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Recent Developments</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Since our previous evidence, the Government has published the UK’s Open Government Part</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">nership National Action Plan</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and initial National Information Infrastructure</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">These documents illustrate, as the Chair has remarked during oral evidence, that Government is “very willing in principle but finding it very hard in practice to be enthusiasti</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">c about open data”. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Government has made a reasonable first attempt at creating a National Information Infrastructure (NII) within a tight timeframe. It is useful to understand what information </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">government holds</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. It is also useful to understand, from th</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">e potential users of that data, what the potential of that data is.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">But the output of this crowd-sourced exercise is too broad and too rooted in the status-quo, rather than based on an assessment of what’s now needed. There is therefore a risk that the foc</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">us is too diffuse. As Stefan Shakespeare has argued, while pursuing an Open by Default strategy, Government should also focus on increasing the availability, quality and reliability of a smaller set of high value datasets of the most commonly referenced in</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">formation such as addresses, companies, and essential public services such as schools and hospitals.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There needs to be a more thorough analysis of what a National Information Infrastructure needs to contain. It should not be seen as a convenient aggregatio</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">n of currently released data sets. Such an analysis should involve a broad range of stakeholders including the Government Office of Science. It should consider what is closed that needs to be opened as part of an Open NII and also what data is needed that </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">is not yet captured at all within the Government digital estate.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Further, the National Information Infrastructure must not itself be a “fire and forget” open data initiative. Sustainability is essential, as is up to date data. The Government must act to re</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">lease and to increase the quality of publication of the high priority items within their National Information Infrastructure list.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The UK’s National Action Plan, stemming from the UK’s membership of the Open Government Partnership, is a collection of loose</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ly related initiatives and commitments. Each individually is laudable. We particularly support the use of legislation to provide a guaranteed supply of local government data - this will give real confidence to data users, in both the public and private sec</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">tors, who can start to rely on the data. However as a set of commitments, the National Action Plan does not come together to give the UK the truly coherent Open Data Strategy the country needs. Open data’s use as a tool for open government should be just o</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ne part of this national strategy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Since our previous evidence, the Open Knowledge Foundation has published the Open Data Index 2013, and the Web Foundation and Open Data Institute have published the Open Data Barometer 2013. Both these measures show the U</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">K’s global leadership in open data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The UK has attained its leading position by doing several relatively easy things for government. The challenge is now to start to do some of the harder things: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">publish currently closed data as open data</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">increase the qua</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">lity of publication of important datasets</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">invest in training civil servants to support that publication and to understand how to use open data for policy benefit</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">These activities are hard, but they are the activities that are likely to bring the biggest im</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">pact. The focus on the Postcode Address File (PAF) during the evidence sessions is because its release as open data would have had a big knock-on impact on a range of other datasets that cannot now be opened, with large potential savings across the public </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">sector. Without address information, the National Information Infrastructure is missing a fundamental component. The government needs to consider how an Open Address Database can be secured.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="h.skymau8fftgc"></a><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Open Data for Everyone</span></h2><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">We noticed that during oral evidence some </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">people said that companies (particularly big multinational companies) should pay for data that is created by government. This is to misunderstand the modern networked economy and the transformative value of open data. The barriers in the use of government </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">data by all types of organisation are not so much about paying fees as the licensing restrictions associated with closed data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">With an early mover advantage, the UK stands to benefit from the adoption and use of its open data by business, including by big </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">multinational companies. The opportunity is to attract inward investment to the UK, because large companies see the benefit of developing new products and services here, combining and using a variety of sources of high quality open data. The government sho</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">uld welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">exploitation of its free, open data, by large multinationals, because of the investment that also brings. This inward investment helps create jobs in the UK and furthers the UK’s lead in open data expertise.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The idea of differential charging between large and small companies is superficially appealing but fundamentally misunderstands the economics of data. We will get the most benefits from data when it can flow freely to where it is needed, whether that flow </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">takes it through large or small companies. Introducing barriers, especially legal barriers through closed licensing, inhibits that flow and prevents us from realising the full benefits from the data created by government.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Another aspect of widening access </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">to open data is to consider how it can be used in school curricula and the more general challenge of how we build capability in the area of data literacy generally and data science in particular. See for example the recently published UK Data Capability St</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">rategy</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> from BIS and the recent e-Skills report</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="h.1ljpgoic5pgp"></a><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Procurement</span></h2><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">We strongly support Tom Steinberg’s comments about the crucial role of procurement policy in facilitating the publication of open data. We would echo his call for new IT systems to include </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">publication of open data at low or zero marginal cost as a basic technical requirement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">We would additionally like to see open data publication written into every government contract. We would like to see performance data and aggregate administrative data </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">arising from the performance of public services published as a matter of course, including when the service is provided by the private sector under contract.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="h.quex3b1cxzkc"></a><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Trading Funds and Regulation</span></h2><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The idea that the Trading Fund model is incompatible with open data, </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">is being disproved by the enlightened policies of the Land Registry and Companies House, both of which are moving towards a 100% open model, supported through registration fees. It is evidently possible for Trading Funds to publish open data, in a way that</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> is consistent with their commercial activities, just as private companies do. There is no inherent reason why Trading Funds can’t also be leaders in open data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The transposition of the new revisions to the EU Directive on Re-use of Public Sector Informati</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">on into UK law will highlight questions about the role of regulation around charging for data and preferential access to information. What is clear is that government can minimise the cost of bureaucracy and regulation arising from the new legislation if a</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ll public sector organisations publish their data as open data.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">November 2013</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]<